Alia pluscula huiuscemodi contuli cum Polyphemo, quae nec curae publicae nec lex illa inter nos ἀμνηστίας patitur hic describi, nisi forte μνησίκακος haberi velim. Proinde, mi Erasme‚ si amici- tiae nostrae eam quam tu reconciliationem, ego continuationem interpretari soleo, seruatam perpetuo optas, fac ista tua epistola vel, si mauis, libello cognoscant homines vcl me eum non esse quem tuis coloribus ita depictum suspicantur vel alienis dolis fuisse tunc 10 a me abalienatum; ego vero quantum in me est dabo operam sedulo vt percipias multis modis nullum esse qui te magis amet quam ego, id quod libentius faciam quum perfecte videro μὴ οὕτως εἶναι σὲ ταχυπειθῆ, id quod de te solum apud amicos vel vno verbo conqueri aliquando consueui, quum de iis quae abs te in me haud amice scripta essent in sermonem incideremus.

Sed considerare debes, mi frater, multos esse qui, quum neutrum nostrum ament, 1103 111101 1103 hostes facere studeant; alioqui si vel te solum amarent, nequaquam hominum mei similium animos in te concitarent. Debes et illud tecum reputare, malo fato meo me vel inuitum in aulica vita versari, in qua quum ὁ φθόνος δεινὸς τύραννος maxime dominetur, nihil mirum videri debet multos esse qui mihi male velint, non magis quia in me aliquid inuidia dignum videant, aut quia se a me vel hilum offensos cognoscant, scd quia tanta est improbitas iniquitasque istius stupidi malique secli, vt cum Catullo epistolam finiam, neque alias causas multis recenseam quibus isti, ignauum fuci pecus, sibi auferri vel nihil agentibus putant quidquid tot meis laboribus, tot periculis a principibus datur.

Vale et posthac a me epistolas expecta ex Italia iucundiore argumento, vt spero, et veris amicis verisque fratribus Germanis dignas. Iterum vale et saluta praeceptorem mihi charissimum dominum Berum, si istic est, meo nomine, vel per literas, si abest.

2680. FROM JEROME ALEANDER. Vatican MS. Lat. 8075, f. 73 v0.

[The letter-book of Aleander (see Ep. 2638 introd.) from which this letter derives, contains five letters of Aleander 10 Ε103111113; of which the first, Ep. 256, is separated from the other four by twenty folios. The others, Epp. 2638-9, 2079—80, are copied consecutively. The fact that this letter follows immediately on Ep. 2679 led Paquier to suppose that it was 0 post- script to it; but (1) it bears neither date nor place; (2) Ep. 2679 seems to have been carried by Polyphemus, whereas the letter to which this is a postscript is stated to have been carried by the imperial post; (3) it seems unlikely that Aleander writing from Ratisbon in 1532 would mention in a merely 0031101 fashion the likelihood of his seeing Erasmus in person at a near date. On these grounds, though for convenience we have placed the letter here, we are inclined to date it as belonging to the period 1520-1.
